                    h4(data-title="Thinking") Why
                    h6 Why are we building this? What problems are we trying to solve?
                    p As a working photographer I ran into the same friction after every shoot. Clients needed to review proof images and choose which ones they wanted retouched, but the available tools were either too expensive or broken for how real selection decisions actually get made.
                    p The SaaS proofing platforms on the market charged <strong>$200–300/year</strong> with storage caps, gallery expiration dates, and a one-at-a-time viewing experience that hadn't evolved in years. The core design failure: when a client is choosing between subtle lighting variations or similar poses, they need to see those images <em>together</em> — not flip between them trying to hold one in memory while viewing another.
                    p User interviews confirmed what I was experiencing firsthand. Clients weren't struggling with the concept of rating images — they were struggling with the inability to hold multiple similar images in view at the same time. The market had built rating tools. Nobody had built a real comparison tool designed for the end client.
                    p I reviewed Adobe Lightroom's Survey Mode and Capture One's online collaboration gallery as reference points. Both had relevant pieces but neither solved the client-facing problem: Survey Mode is desktop-only and client-inaccessible; Capture One limits comparison to two images.

